g.text: Product creation must be done (safely) on a step-by-step base

g.title: Folded Corner
g.desc: The Builder pattern enables ‘fine’ control over object (=Prod...

g.text: The Builder pattern enables ‘fine’ control over object (=Product) creation. This means, it is possible to perform a creation step, process something else and perform another creation step. The Builder returns a valid product, after all creation steps are completed. This is different from the Factory patterns. The Factory patterns create a product and return it immediately. The Product, in the Builder pattern, often exposes its internals to allow the step-by-step creation. This means a client might perform these constructions steps. However, this might endanger the validity of the Product. A constraining factor could be that the construction steps must be performed is a specific order or none of them can be skipped. The Builder pattern might be applied to ensure the validity of the Product.

g.title: Folded Corner.15
g.desc: The Builder pattern compliments the Single Responsibility pri...

g.text: The Builder pattern compliments the Single Responsibility principle by separating object construction logic from client code. This enhances the readability, reusability, stability and testability of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where client fulfills the step-by-step Product constructing responsibility. Readability, because the client does not contain the clustering, constraining and orchestrating logic to compose the Product. The Builder pattern extracts this logic into a separate Director and Builder class. This ensures a more ‘focused’ client. Reusability, because object construction logic can be shared amongst multiple clients. In contrast, situating the construction logic within the client would complicate or disallow reusability, resulting in duplication. Duplication results in an increase in maintenance effort for both production and test code. Stability, because the Product construction steps are constrained. The Director constrains the construction sequence and exact steps to produce the Product. This ‘invites’ clients to reuse those steps, which clarifies design intent and prevents malfunctions. As an addition to the stability aspect, the separation of construction steps from the client reduces the chance of breaking code unrelated to the change. In case client requires change, the construction steps (=Director) are not impacted directly and visa versa. Testability, because product construction steps are isolated from client code. This shrinks the problem window of the client. Shrinkage of the problem window enables isolated testing. Isolated testing enables finding malfunctions faster.

g.title: Folded Corner.20
g.desc: The Builder pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by ...

g.text: The Builder pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by allowing the introduction of new object representations without modifying or duplicating the object construction steps. This enhance the stability and reusability of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where object construction logic is directly dependent on concrete object representation. Stability, because new representations (=Products) can be added without modifying the construction logic (=Director) directly. This minimizes the chance of breaking stable product and test code. In contrast, Director being dependent on concrete Product might result in change when a new Product is introduced. Reusability, because the same construction steps (=Director) can be used with different Product representations. In contrast, Director being dependent on concrete Product directly might result in Director duplication for each new representation. Duplication results in an increase in maintenance effort for both product and test code.

g.title: Folded Corner.41
g.desc: The Builder pattern enables abstracting away and preventing C...

g.text: The Builder pattern enables abstracting away and preventing Constructor Telescoping. Constructor Telescoping is overloading the constructor of a class to allow creation of different variants. The disadvantage of this approach is that it makes usability and readability hard. Clients need to remember the order of the parameters and call the correct constructor corresponding to the object variant. The class could be refactored to use setters instead. This in turn could be used by the Builder pattern to create the product in a safe, easy and reusable way. However, it might be undesirable to change existing code. In this case, the Builder pattern can encapsulate the Telescope Constructors and provide a simplistic construction interface to the (new) clients.

g.desc: The same construction logic applies to different representati...
g.text: The same construction logic applies to different representations

g.title: Folded Corner.53
g.desc: The main goal of the Builder pattern is to re-use the same co...

g.text: The main goal of the Builder pattern is to re-use the same construction logic for different object representations. A common problem: construction steps for object x and object y are identical, however both objects have different interfaces (=representations). The Builder pattern can be applied as a solution to prevent duplication of the construction logic. The Builder pattern identifies the produced objects as Products, the Builder as the class constructing the Products and the Director ‘orchestrating’ and clustering the construction steps/logic. The Director serves as a (kind of) Façade (see Façade design pattern) by providing the client a simplified construction interface of the Product. The Builder interface allows the Director to shuffle between different Builders. The concrete Builder serves as an Adapter (see Adapter design pattern) between Builder and Product interface. The combination of concrete Builder and interface enable the Director to re-use identical construction steps to construct different Products. The produced Products may have complete different representations, so the builder is responsible for retrieving the final Product.

g.title: Rectangle.56
g.desc: Delegate object creation to a separate class
g.text: Delegate object creation to a separate class

g.title: Folded Corner.95
g.desc: The Builder pattern prescribes delegation of ‘complex’ object...

g.text: The Builder pattern prescribes delegation of ‘complex’ object creation to a separate class. A common Use Case might be that the construction of an object requires multiple steps, dependencies and calculations. Delegation of this logic, to a separate class, can be beneficial to keep client code more ‘focused’ and allow sharing. The Builder pattern, more specific the Director, centralizes the object (=Product) construction steps to gain these benefits. In this case, the Builder pattern is applicable, even if there is a single representation (=Product). A single representation might result in the Builder class to be redundant. The Product can then be directly constructed by the Director. The Product provides setters (JavaBeans Pattern) and the Director ‘guards’ the Product until it is constructed. This implementation might be close to a Factory form, except that the ‘full’ construction of the product is on a step-by-step base.

g.title: Folded Corner.109
g.desc: The Builder design pattern entails both the negative and posi...

g.text: The Builder design pattern entails both the negative and positive side of the Open Closed principle. The abstraction between Director and concrete Builder allow new Builders and Products to be introduced, without modification of the Director. I.e. the same construction logic (=Director) can be shared with different representations (=Products). This ensures code stability and reusability at the expensive of debuggability and navigability. Indirection has negative affect on debugging, navigating and comprehending the code. The indirection, between Product (=representation) and Director (=construction logic), is caused by the abstract and concrete Builder. The necessity of this indirection should be well-considered. The Abstract and Concrete builder might be redundant in case a single representation is constructed by the Director and this is unlikely to change. The Director might still be useful to allow sharing, delegating and constraining Product creation.

g.title: Folded Corner.114
g.desc: The Builder design pattern entails both the negative and posi...

g.text: The Builder design pattern entails both the negative and positive side of the Single Responsibility principle. Delegating object creation to a separate class introduces an additional form of indirection. This indirection will make it harder to comprehend the dependency model of the client. The reusability, readability and stability the pattern provides, should outweigh the decrease in comprehend-ability of the dependency model. Whenever this is not the case, it might be more suitable to construct an object on a step-by-step base within the client directly.
